nd line since the mid-2010s is strongly positive.)</p><p> As a coda, one thing that irks me is that the way America&#39;s housing system works makes it very easy to complain <em>no matter what&#39;s happening</em> to housing prices and mortgage rates. If house prices are rising, you can complain about how hard it is for young people to afford a home. But if house prices are falling, you can complain about how middle-class wealth is being demolished (since most middle-class Americans have most of their wealth in their house). No matter what happens, you can tell a negative story about it. This is a product of the fact that America chose long ago to make real estate our main middle-class wealth vehicle, instead of stocks and bonds like they do in Japan. But in any case, I wish the people who complain about these things would imagine what their ideal situation for housing prices would look like.</p><h4> 3. A wonderful debate on AI and economic growth</h4><p> <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-462">Read more</a></p> ; 
