="image-caption"> “我很可爱，我是朋克摇滚” - 来自 Milady Maker 系列（Remilia，2021 年）。 </figcaption></figure></div><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/im-cute-im-punk-rock?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoyNDA5OTk2LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxMzU5NTUzMDEsImlhdCI6MTY5MjU3NzU2MSwiZXhwIjoxNjk1MTY5NTYxLCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMzUzNDUiLCJzdWIiOiJwb3N0LXJlYWN0aW9uIn0.R8i0fowoidaN6si20pZ5E5fLZqmx3yiZftUqBGNfjL4&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/im-cute-im-punk-rock?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoyNDA5OTk2LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxMzU5NTUzMDEsImlhdCI6MTY5MjU3NzU2MSwiZXhwIjoxNjk1MTY5NTYxLCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMzUzNDUiLCJzdWIiOiJwb3N0LXJlYWN0aW9uIn0.R8i0fowoidaN6si20pZ5E5fLZqmx3yiZftUqBGNfjL4"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
Can unions and industrial policy coexist? They had better learn how to, and quickly. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/can-unions-and-industrial-policy https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/can-unions-and-industrial-policyNoah Smith Thu, 10 Aug 2023 10:01:46 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg" width="1456" height="1139" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1139,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:509301,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe518537d-a98e-4a9b-aa71-90fdccdd91fb_2000x1564.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></figure></div><p>在拜登总统的领导下，美国启动了一项雄心勃勃的新经济计划。通过《减少通货膨胀法案》和《CHIPS法案》，我们与里根-克林顿的“新自由主义”时代彻底决裂，<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-new-industrial-policy-explained">转向产业政策</a>。这是智力上的胜利，但还不是<em>经济上的</em>胜利。仅仅决定以不同的方式做事是不够的。你必须真正产生结果，我们的新计划是失败的。</p><p>就拜登的产业政策而言，成功与否的考验将是绿色能源和半导体能否真正<em>建成</em>。我在这里看到三种可能的结果：</p><ul><li><p>结果 1：大量绿色能源和半导体建成。</p></li><li><p>结果2：政府花费了大量资金，但绿色能源和半导体的建设却很少，因为这一过程受到监管、邻避主义、繁重的项目要求、熟练劳动力短缺和成本过高等综合因素的阻碍。</p></li><li><p>结果 3：共和党的政治反对派和监管/成本障碍相结合，从一开始就阻止了政府资金的支出。</p></li></ul><p>结果1是完全成功，而结果3是彻底失败。结果 2 是最复杂的情​​况。这将是一个<em>短期的政治成功</em>，并且可能会取悦政府资金流入的一系列民主党利益集团。但因为它不会导致生产出对普通美国人有用的商品，所以这将是一次<em>经济失败</em>。最终，经济失败将转化为<em>长期的政治失败</em>，因为绝大多数不属于民主党利益集团的选民认为他们的钱并没有真正得到任何东西，并决定放弃拜登经济学并返回里根经济学又延续了两代人。</p><p>因此，我认为产业政策的支持者努力避免结果 2 是个好主意。埃兹拉·克莱因（Ezra Klein）对此表示同意，这就是为什么他一直倡导他所谓的“<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2021/09/19/opinion/supply-side-progressivism.html">供给侧进步主义</a>”。这基本上是这样的概念：渐进式产业政策的<em>目标</em>——例如经济脱碳——应该优先于我们实现这些目标所使用的<em>方法</em>。埃兹拉认为，我们应该努力促进工会的发展，听取社区团体的意见等等，但不要达到实际上最终破坏产业政策本身的程度。我<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/progressives-need-to-embrace-progress">忍不住同意。</a></p><p>克莱因在进步运动中的批评者——作家大卫·达延(David Dayen)、颇具影响力的罗斯福研究所的人士等——不幸地倾向于严重错误地描述他的论点，声称“供给侧进步主义”意味着<a href="https://prospect.org/economy/2023-05-25-liberalism-that-builds-power/">废除《清洁空气法案》</a>和工作场所安全法律、取消民主、<a href="https://twitter.com/toddntucker/status/1684588135919886337">将工会和环保主义者</a>踢出进步运动、在黑人社区<a href="https://twitter.com/SuzMKahn/status/1689010093126455297">设置“不需要的基础设施”</a>等等。事实上，正如埃里克·莱维茨（Eric Levitz） <a href="https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2023/08/the-case-against-supply-side-liberalism-is-weak.html">在最近的一篇专栏中所解释的那样</a>，这些指控都是似是而非的——它们要么完全是凭空捏造的，要么直接与克莱因所写的内容相矛盾。</p><p>但撇开恶意的漫画不谈，这里的争论有一些真正的实质内容。考虑一下工会的作用，它是一个重要的民主党支持团体，几乎肯定会在产业政策的实施中发挥重要作用。</p><h4>工会并不总是让建立起来变得更加困难——但有时却会如此</h4><p>以亚利桑那州台积电工厂为例。这家工厂由世界顶级芯片制造商建造，是拜登振兴美国半导体行业计划的核心。但由于缺乏懂得如何建造半导体工厂的美国工人，这个旗舰项目现已<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2023/07/20/tsmc-delays-start-of-arizona-chip-factory-that-will-build-apple-chips.html">推迟一年</a>：</p><blockquote><p>台积电董事长刘马克在周四的财报电话会议上对分析师表示，该公司没有足够的熟练工人来按照最初的时间表在该工厂安装先进设备。该公司<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2021/10/16/tsmc-taiwanese-chipmaker-ramping-production-to-end-chip-shortage.html">此前预计</a>将于 2024 年开始生产 5 纳米芯片。</p><p>刘说，该公司正在努力从台湾派遣技术人员来培训当地工人，以帮助加快安装速度。</p></blockquote><p>这显然不是那种单纯通过提高工资就能解决的用工荒问题。你可以每年付给我 10,000,000 美元来安装芯片制造设备，我最终可以学会如何做到这一点，但这需要一段时间。我无法通过阅读维基百科来了解它；我需要有人曾经做过这件事来训练我。毕竟，这些是人类有史以来建造的<a href="https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/world-news/the-tech-cold-wars-most-complicated-machine-thats-out-of-chinas-reach/articleshow/84132902.cms?from=mdr">最复杂的机器之一</a>。</p><p>美国根本就没有很多人知道如何安装这些设备，因为我们已经很长时间没有建造很多芯片工厂了。这就是台积电派出自己的人员来培训美国工人并帮助安装的原因。</p><p>但令人抓狂的是，美国一些工会现在正<a href="https://9to5mac.com/2023/08/07/us-tsmc-plant-petition/">试图阻止这些台湾工人</a>来华！</p><blockquote><p> Controversy over the first ever US <a href="https://9to5mac.com/guides/tsmc/">TSMC</a> plant aren&#39;t going away – especially plans for around 500 Taiwanese construction workers to be flown in.</p><p> A petition has been created, calling on senators and members of Congress to block the visas needed to bring in their foreign workers…The company says that these workers have experience of setting up similar plants in Taiwan, so will help with faster and more cost-effective working.</p><p> However, unions say it breaks a promise to create jobs for American workers…The Arizona Pipe Trades 469 union has <a href="https://www.votervoice.net/AZPipeTrades/Campaigns/106830/Respond">started a petition</a> to block the issuing of these visas.</p></blockquote><p> This is, in a word, nuts. American pipefitters simply do not know the technical details of installing ultraviolet lithography machinery. They need someone to teach them before they can do it, and the people who can teach them live in Taiwan. Blocking these overseas workers doesn&#39;t help anybody, least of all American workers, who will be left without wages if no factory gets built.</p><p> So it&#39;s clearly <em>possible</em> for unions to block industrial policy from working. Nor is this the only such example; witness the union attempt to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-deep-divide-on-automation-hangs-over-west-coast-port-labor-talks-11654803112">stop ports from using automation</a> , even as supply chain snarls drove up inflation. And yet at the same time, both US history and the recent experience of other countries shows that unions don&#39;t <em>have to</em> be a barrier to high-tech manufacturing.</p><p> First, let&#39;s look at history. Perhaps the most successful industrial policy in US history was the World War 2 effort, which turned the US into the world&#39;s dominant high-tech manufacturer. This awesome success coincided with a historic rise in the fraction of unionized workers, thanks to <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Industrial_Recovery_Act_of_1933">a pair</a> of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Labor_Relations_Act_of_1935">laws</a> the Roosevelt Administration passed in 1933 and 1935 that made collective bargaining easier. </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg" width="688" height="413.531914893617" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:452,&quot;width&quot;:752,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:688,&quot;bytes&quot;:69496,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F32be27b8-f31a-45b0-80a4-ed03f825ba0f_752x452.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> BoogaLouie, CC BY-SA 3.0, via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Union_membership_in_us_1930-2010.png">Wikimedia Commons</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Roosevelt administration certainly clashed with unions on occasion during this time period, and strikes did disrupt wartime production to a small extent, but overall the relationship between unions and the government was <a href="https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/documents/letter-walter-p-reuther-extending-greetings-the-15th-constitutional-convention-the">a constructive and effective one</a> . The progressive goals of unionization and <a href="https://www.nber.org/papers/w24587">broadly shared prosperity</a> were ultimately aligned with the industrialist goals of winning WW2 and building up US high-tech manufacturing.</p><p> Of course, that was a long time ago, and technology has changed. But there&#39;s little reason to believe that unions are incompatible with high-tech manufacturing in the modern day. <a href="https://conversableeconomist.blogspot.com/2016/09/union-density-and-collective-bargaining.html">Consider the fact</a> that countries like Germany and Japan have considerably higher unionization rates than the US, and Germany has <em>much</em> higher rates of collective bargaining coverage, due to something called <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sectoral_collective_bargaining">sectoral bargaining</a> that lets even non-union workers be covered by union agreements: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg" width="677" height="781" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:781,&quot;width&quot;:677,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:135497,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa3951b72-8cf9-4cc8-b387-6fb788a4d4fa_677x781.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> But despite much higher unionization rates, both countries still have much more of their economy dedicated to manufacturing than the US does, and have deindustrialized much less than the US has over the past two decades: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg" width="1012" height="813" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:813,&quot;width&quot;:1012,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:110452,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F171dbe8d-8882-4d70-8cdd-fc0aa9c7c946_1012x813.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NV.IND.MANF.ZS?end=2022&amp;locations=DE-US-JP&amp;start=1998">World Bank</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> That doesn&#39;t mean there&#39;s no conflict between labor and management in those countries&#39; manufacturing industries. Germany&#39;s <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/features/2023-04-11/germany-s-economic-future-depends-on-its-non-fortune-500-companies?sref=R8NfLgwS">famed “mittelstand” manufacturers</a> , for instance, often <a href="https://www.economist.com/business/2020/02/01/deutschland-ag-rethinks-workers-role-in-management">try to get out of the country&#39;s requirement</a> that labor be given board representation (a policy called “co-determination”). And unionization has declined over time in both <a href="https://assets.bwbx.io/images/users/iqjWHBFdfxIU/iPOZFWTi_w38/v0/-1x-1.png">Japan</a> and <a href="https://www.statista.com/statistics/416156/trade-union-density-germany-y-on-y/">Germany</a> , due to the pressures of globalization. But these countries&#39; success in manufacturing relative to the US, despite their higher collective bargaining coverage, indicates that unions are not incompatible with manufacturing excellence.</p><p> Nor is this the only such example we should look at. Some people try to blame unions for America&#39;s higher infrastructure costs relative to other developed countries. But those countries are actually much more unionized than the US, and their unions are <a href="https://www.economist.com/the-economist-explains/2014/03/17/why-french-trade-unions-are-so-strong">politically stronger</a> as well. Alon Levy, who has made a more careful study of infrastructure cost differences than perhaps any other human being alive, concludes that<a href="https://pedestrianobservations.com/2019/01/08/meme-weeding-unions-and-construction-costs/">little of the cost differential is due to unions</a> . US construction wages <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2017-05-31/the-u-s-has-forgotten-how-to-do-infrastructure?sref=R8NfLgwS">aren&#39;t even much higher</a> than wages in other countries. Although union rules in some regions do force transit agencies to hire too many staff, Levy concludes that this is a minor factor.</p><p> In other words, strong unions are very compatible with cheap infrastructure construction — which is exactly what we need to decarbonize America.</p><h4> Unions shouldn&#39;t go away, but some of them need to change their approach</h4><p> In other words, unions do impose some cost on industrial policy, but it doesn&#39;t have to be a crippling or prohibitive cost. And as the example of World War 2 show, there are political benefits of aligning the interests of labor and industrialist planners. And there are signs that those political benefits are still achievable today — witness how <a href="https://darrellowens.substack.com/p/yimby-triumph-in-california">the shift of many unions to the YIMBY camp</a> in California was what enabled many of the pro-housing bills now being passed by the state legislature.</p><p> Thus, there is no reason to think that union-busting should be a part of our industrial policy, or that unions should be expelled from the progressive coalition. At the same time, the examples of the Taiwanese construction workers and resistance to automated ports show that American unions sometimes really do act in ways that frustrate the goals of progressives and industrialists alike. If industrial policy is to succeed, they need to stop doing that.</p><p> Supply-side progressives therefore need to think of ways to align the interests of the unions and the industrialists. That might involve giving labor more of a seat at the table when making industrial policy, so that unions understand that new technologies and foreign workers aren&#39;t threats to their livelihoods. That could mean some variant of German co-determination, or simply including a few prominent union leaders in the planning process for the implementation of the CHIPS Act and the IRA. The goal here is to get American unions out of the wild-eyed defensive crouch that they&#39;ve been in for the last 40 years, and convince them that things that they previously perceived as threats — new technologies and foreign workers — now represent opportunities instead.</p><p> Meanwhile, the people at the Roosevelt Institute need to stop <a href="https://twitter.com/toddntucker/status/1684588135919886337">acting like every criticism</a> of union behavior is a prelude to union-busting and a fracturing of the Democratic coalition. That kind of panicky reaction is also a sort of defensive crouch, born of the Clinton years when the only way Dems could win elections was by making concessions to Reaganomics. It&#39;s not 1996 anymore; progressives are now setting the economic policy agenda. They can afford to tell unions “No, don&#39;t do it like that, do it like this instead” without seeming weak and disunited.</p><p> Ultimately, people like David Dayen and the Roosevelt Institute people are right that progressive industrialism needs to build power in order to succeed. But the power to merely appropriate resources from the federal government is far inferior to the power to create prosperity out of nothing for the whole country. That is something the supply-side progressives understand, to their great credit. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/can-unions-and-industrial-policy?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoyNDA5OTk2LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxMzU4ODY5ODIsImlhdCI6MTY5MjU3NzU2MSwiZXhwIjoxNjk1MTY5NTYxLCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMzUzNDUiLCJzdWIiOiJwb3N0LXJlYWN0aW9uIn0.TTyGxnTTqxgVK30TM90sux_3_a2IIkGCAkJo723keoM&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/can-unions-and-industrial-policy?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&token=eyJ1c2VyX2lkIjoyNDA5OTk2LCJwb3N0X2lkIjoxMzU4ODY5ODIsImlhdCI6MTY5MjU3NzU2MSwiZXhwIjoxNjk1MTY5NTYxLCJpc3MiOiJwdWItMzUzNDUiLCJzdWIiOiJwb3N0LXJlYWN0aW9uIn0.TTyGxnTTqxgVK30TM90sux_3_a2IIkGCAkJo723keoM"><span>分享</span></a></p>; 
